Right-wing populists win in Austria, they have 29 percent of the total
According to preliminary results, the early parliamentary elections in Austria brought a sensitive weakening of the two parties forming the current big coalition, as well as a notorious strengthening of populist parties.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP), where the position of current President Wilhelm Molterer is seriously threatened, suffered significant losses.
On the other hand, the electoral leader of the Union for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), the governor of Carinthia, Jörg Haider, is preparing a triumphant return to the political scene at the national level.
According to preliminary results, the Socialists (SPÖ) remain, with 29.8 percent of the votes, the country’s leading political force, however, compared to the 2006 elections, they lost 5.5 percent of the votes.
The ÖVP, which with 25.6 percent lost nine percent of the votes, ended up even worse.
These are the worst results of the two major post-war parties; especially for the popular party, which triggered early elections, the outcome is literally catastrophic.
Even in early July, when the ÖVP left the coalition, the People's Party had a considerable advance over the SPÖ.
But voters clearly punished them for letting the government collapse.
From the first reactions to the results, speculations about the possible resignation of the party leader and current deputy chancellor Wilhelm Molterer, were pronounced.
Observers estimate that this could happen as early as Monday, during the extraordinary council of the party’s leadership.
Such an evolution would facilitate a priori the way to the outcome of the election which remains the most likely, namely the renewal of the large coalition SPÖ and ÖVP.
Nevertheless, given the strengthening of the two right-wing populist parties – the Free Party (FPÖ) would have won 18 percent and BZÖ eleven percent of the votes – the Socialists expressed at the same time the fear of a repetition of 1999, when the People’s Party agreed with the populists (at the time, the FPÖ was still unified, it was in 2005 that the BZÖ separated) on a common government, which even triggered sanctions from the European Union.
Haider, who has already stated that he was ready to collaborate with any party and that he planned to return to Vienna, on the national political scene, apparently based on this development.
The last party to have access to parliament was the Greens, but these lost slightly and fell, among the Austrian political parties, from third to fifth position.
Obviously, no other party crossed the four percent threshold and entered parliament.
