The ‘bee car’ that avoids collisions
To advance the development of accidents prevention technologies, Nissan inspired itself, this time, from nature, especially bees.
A Japanese company has created a robot that, by imitating the flight of bees, avoids accidents.
It is called Bio-Mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, and represents the first steps towards collision prevention technologies.
The engineers at the Advanced Technical Center at Nissan Motor Co. developed this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Advanced Science and Technology Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Chief Public Relations Officer for Technology and Brand Management Research and Development, the BR23C represents the rise of Nissan’s safety shield.
This robot will allow the brand’s vehicles to prevent collisions.
During its flight, each bee created its own personal space in an oval shape that resembles Nissan’s safety shield.
But the most important are the eyes composed of the bee, able to see from an angle of more than 300 degrees and in all directions, which allows it to fly uninterruptedly inside its own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, the engineers developed what is known as a Laser Range Finder.
It detects obstacles at a distance of two meters and within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to that object and sends a signal to the microprocessor, immediately, to avoid the obstacle.
“When it detects an obstacle, the small robot will mimic the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by twisting its wheels 90 degrees or more to avoid collision.
The biggest difference from any other existing system is that the escape manoeuvre is entirely instinctive.
If that were the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Movement Laboratory and chief engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot be diverted up or down, or diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and depending on what its wheels allow it, and not in infinite directions like bees.
For this reason, Nissan used a rotation function, but also acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot can avoid obstacles.
“Each second this device only has to process information and act according to that data.
It does not need to retain the information or intuitive logic of pre-maneuvering, which is why it can work continuously with only a few dozen KB of memory.
It may be surprising, but we’re not talking about gigabytes of memory, or even megabytes.”
This represents the first car to develop new instant collision prevention technologies, a technology that will be introduced into production cars in about a decade, according to Nissan.
The robot runs with lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible application of this technology in the future could be the adaptation of this device on a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to his destination while avoiding obstacles on the road.
