The terms presented on Monday also show that the deal has been modified in recent days: Last Monday, Morgan simply announced that it would sell up to 20% of its shares to the Japanese for about $8.5 billion.
“A week ago,” said Toshihide Mizuno, MUFG’s chief executive, “we thought the participation would be entirely ordinary shares.
But given the current situation in the economy and the market, we wanted to minimize the risks and cover ourselves.”
Based on the weighted average price, MUFG will pay its Morgan Stanley securities 7% below their accounting value.
And the operation will result in a dilution of about 20% of profit per share.
The agreement stipulates that MUFG will be able to convert half of its preferential securities into ordinary shares within one year if they trade more than 50% above the conversion price, or about $47, over a given period.
Morgan Stanley assures that MUFG’s capital will enable it to seize investment opportunities, strengthen its balance sheet and increase its liquidity.
A spokeswoman for the group, however, declined to give details on the strategic plans of the two new allies.
Following MUFG’s investment, Morgan Stanley is expected to display a Tier One solvency ratio of around 15%, one of the best in the industry.
Morgan said he has "significantly" eased his balance sheet since the end of August.
The last few weeks have been challenging for the group, which saw its stock price melt by half as the cost of insurance against default risk on its debt dropped.
This cost fell on Monday but remained at a high level, around 12%.
Last week, Goldman Sachs, the only other “survivor” of Wall Street’s major investment banks after the bankruptcies of Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers and Merrill Lynch’s acquisition, announced it had raised $15 billion, partly from Berkshire Hathaway, Warren Buffett’s group.
Rafael Correa in Quito on Monday.
Re-founding the republic around the socialism of the 21st century.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, along with his counterparts and friends, it was the third time that a draft of a new Constitution was put to the vote.
Mission accomplished since 64% of voters voted "yes" in the referendum, according to official results covering 80% of the votes.
According to these results, the “no” received 28%, 7% of the votes were null and 0.7% were blank votes.
In order for the draft constitution to be passed, it needed half the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two polls conducted at the exit of the polling stations and a count of a non-governmental organization had announced a large victory of the "yes", placing it between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa claimed in the night of Sunday to Monday the victory of his constitution.
“The Constitution triumphed overwhelmingly,” he said, congratulating the Ecuadorians on the headquarters of the governorate of Guayaquil, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
As of course, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chávez and Morales as well as his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The vote, which took place quietly according to the observation mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), dealt with a text of 444 points consolidating the “new socialism” defended by the president.
The draft constitution dedicates the state’s power over the economy, reserving to it the “development planning” of a country that lives essentially from the extraction of oil by foreign companies and currencies sent by its emigrants.
Led by Correa, elected in 2006, the bill also grants enhanced powers to the head of state, who will be able to carry out up to two consecutive four-year terms and will have the possibility to dissolve the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he will use this power and fight for a new term in February 2009.
The Constitution also consolidates the principle of free health and education services that the president has begun to establish in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
Finally, it provides for a ban on the presence of foreign troops, which will end the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for U.S. drug operations.
Thirteen hostages released in Chad
An Egyptian commando launched an assault on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight accompanies captured ten days ago.
They are in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions held captive for ten days in the desert were returned to the Egyptian capital on Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they were liberated by an Egyptian commando in Chad.
Apparently in shape, the hostages arrived around 15:30 a.m. on a special aircraft at the al-Maza military base, which is located at Cairo’s international airport.
They were immediately transferred, without being able to speak to the press, by helicopter to the hospital of Maadi, a residential suburb of Cairo, to undergo examinations.
They are in "good health" and "no ransom has been paid" to the kidnappers, Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garanna said.
Captured on September 19 during a 4x4 safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, this group of hostages had been bullied from one cache to another by 35 unknown kidnappers.
It includes 11 tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - as well as eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the agency Aegyptous, organizing the safari.
An Egyptian security official said 30 special forces members, dispatched on board two helicopters, launched the assault in the night just before dawn.
“An exchange of shots took place, and half of the kidnappers were killed, the others fleeing,” said the official, who requested anonymity.
He said 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the lightning unit had been sent to Sudan, where they received support from German and Italian commandos.
Italian Foreign Minister Franco Frattini mentioned from Belgrade, where he is, the role played by secret agents and elements of Italian special forces.
"We must recognize that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and effectiveness of our intelligence men, special forces," he said, without further details.
He also denied the payment of a ransom.
On the eve, the Sudanese army claimed to have intercepted a 4x4 vehicle with the kidnappers on board during a patrol, killing six, including the Chadian leader, and arresting two.
The army claimed that they were linked to a rebel group in Darfur, the Sudan-Unity Liberation Movement (SLA-U), which the movement immediately denied.
The Silent Majority of Culture
A debate on the financing of culture is headlines and occupies the current election campaign.
So much better.
But a part of our cultural life remains forgotten.
Who will stand up to denounce the sums of misery that are given to small museums, archives, archaeological excavations or national historical sites that are starving?
Which politician will dare to remind the federal government that it is neglecting its monuments and heritage buildings?
That in Quebec, like in Canada, we do not have real laws that effectively preserve our heritage?
Did you know that the French government is spending three and a half million euros on restoring the only Château de Chinon in the Loire Valley?
In our American neighbors, it is written in the Constitution of their country that the protection of heritage is part of the culture of Americans and that this heritage must be protected by all citizens, all elected and all government departments, and this, in concert.
In Quebec, at least 40,000 volunteers grouped in 211 societies of history, heritage, archives and genealogy are concerned with researching history, preserving private archives and preserving archaeological remains.
They are often the guard dogs of our heritage, who protest with the energy of despair when promoters and policymakers throw their bulldozers against our old stones and our forgotten cemeteries.
When is a history and heritage tribune?
Benelux governments nationalize part of Fortis bank
The Benelux states are helping the Belgian-Dutch bank, as the first European banking institution in distress following the snowball effect of the credit market crisis in the United States, by partially nationalizing it.
This weekend, the Belgian, Luxembourg and Dutch governments agreed at the highest level on the matter, also appealing to the European Central Bank and the European Commission's competition officer.
In the euro area, the first major crisis in the context of the international financial crisis, which has intensified in more than a year, is for the bank Fortis.
In accordance with the decision taken on Sunday night, the three states will buy back half (up to 49%) of the bank’s capital located in each of the countries.
The bank will undoubtedly sell a portion of its shares, including, first of all, the activities, mainly insurance, which it acquired last year from the Dutch agency ABN Amro.
Last week, Fortis stocks began a dizzying drop.In the second half of the week, serious signs of crisis have already been revealed in the bank.
Analysts agree that with its 85,000 employees, the bank is far too big to go bankrupt.
On Friday alone, the company’s shares fell 12 percent, reaching its lowest level in 14 years.
Since January, the stock has fallen by more than two-thirds of its value.
Taking into account the current value of the shares, the total value of the group’s capital is around €14 billion, which, according to the company’s executives, is unrealistic.
The company's management accuses overseas uncertainty, related to the adoption of the US $700 billion bailout plan, of being the cause of the fall in Fortis shares.
On Monday, the prices increased slightly.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed chairman of the bank, as the new CEO.
The financial institution was also looking for private buyers, but has not yet received a proposal on the substance.
Previously, the Belgian government announced that investors should not worry, they would not lose their money.
No panic was felt in the bank’s clientele circle and no agency was attacked.
In Hungary, Fortis owns independent agencies and has also acquired leasing companies.
A fox in the chicken.
In America, life and health insurance companies often refuse to sign an insurance contract with a candidate, based on information about his or her purchases of medicines.
Information protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
“There are data protection programs that bind the use of prescription information, in all cases, to the consent of the person concerned.
This kind of program must be in independent hands, otherwise it’s like entrusting your chicken to a fox,” Richard Dicket, the creator of the program used to manage prescription drugs, told the Washington Post.
Insurance companies make the insurance premium and insured capital in case of damage dependent on the customer’s health condition, and if they consider the risk too high, they do not even insure it.
In the past, they sent candidates for a medical examination, and they signed an insurance contract with them only after learning about the results.
For ten years, Dick has found a much cheaper procedure: from an identification number, he easily provides himself with pharmacies, data on the person's purchase of medicines in the past eighteen months.
For example, if that person regularly buys high doses of cholesterol reducer, this refers to an extremely high level of fat in the blood, which immediately puts him in a higher risk category.
Several versions of this program are in circulation. Some determine a risk coefficient at the same time, so there is not much more to do to the insurer except paperwork.
Among the disadvantages of this program is the fact that a drug can be used for different purposes.For example, some mixtures can be used against migraine or heat strokes, but can also be effective against depression.
The latter is seen by insurers as an aggravating risk factor, while others do not.
Companies have grown in data research and analysis, and they must ask for permission from the patient before collecting the necessary information from the pharmacy.
From now on, they are forced to do so by the authorities, even though they have not been punished for their faults in the past.
Recently, some companies are also processing the results of laboratory analyses, and linking them with data on drug consumption.
More and more companies have access to data, and control of use is becoming increasingly difficult.
There is a separate law on medical data protection, but its scope extends only to practitioners and insurers.
A bill expanding the circle of authorities’ control over companies specializing in data provision is currently in Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is not enough and that is why he has further developed his program, which would condition the transmission of data to the exclusive consent of the data subject.
This is another question of whether the person concerned is really free to give his or her consent or not, since if he or she refuses, the insurance companies do not sign an insurance contract with him or her.
Thus, and ultimately, the chickens depend on the fox’s kindness.
The overall menu of Marseille
The EU and India are doubling their trade.
Since the European Union and India are very important trade partners for each other, this theme also dominated the agenda of this ninth summit alongside other, largely global issues.
There will also be a summit between France and India on nuclear energy cooperation.
The European Union recognizes that India is a major emerging democratic power that should be given wider voice in international affairs, but member countries have not yet been able to agree on their support to New Delhi for its candidacy as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
They did not delay this issue at the ninth summit held in Marseille.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, as well as the current president of the Union, as well as the President of the Commission José Manuel Barroso and the Head of Foreign Affairs, Javier Solana, welcomed the Prime Minister of India, Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed that in five years, they would double trade, which means an increase of a good hundred billion euros.
Given that between 2000 and 2007, the trade in goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this does not seem to be an ambitious goal.
In this sense, they have legally harmonised the 26 bilateral conventions with India concerning civil flights.
India wants to sign a free trade agreement with the EU by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy has promised to accelerate the negotiations.
The goal is to balance the situation with, on the one hand, India, which is the EU’s largest trading partner, and, on the other hand, New Delhi, which ranks only ninth among EU partners.
The summit focused on global affairs.
The situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan was strongly condemned, as well as all forms of terrorism, and the urgency of holding a UN conference on this subject was discussed.
The completion of the Doha trade cycle has also been called for, although both have a large share in the current failure.
The EU has confirmed that it remains loyal to its energy and climate agenda, including that it wants to reduce its emissions of toxic materials by at least 20 percent by 2020.
India also agreed on this point, as well as the need to pass a global market at next year’s climate conference, and reduce greenhouse gas emissions by fifty percent by 2050.
They also wanted to prevent rising food prices, and supported the convening of an international working meeting to examine the financial crisis.
The head of state of India is travelling to the French capital, where during a bilateral meeting, he prepares to sign an agreement on the peaceful use of atomic energy.
In Paris, French companies are expected to receive orders worth 20 billion euros for the construction of Indian nuclear reactors.
According to the news agency, the deal would last for 15 years.
