The plane of Steve Fossett, the billionaire who disappeared a year ago, has been found.
The remains of the plane of Steve Fosset, the billionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007 while flying over the Nevada desert, have been found.
The debris was found on a plateau at 3,000 meters in the Sierra Nevada area of Mammonth Lakes, on the border between California and Nevada.
Inside the plane, no human remains.
Madera County Sheriff John Anderson dismissed the remaining doubts: "The plane was localized, we sent a team, and now we have confirmation that it is indeed the one on which Steve Fosset was traveling the day he disappeared," he said at a news conference.
The sheriff said no human remains were found on or around the plane.
In February, the 63-year-old billionaire was considered dead.
The U.S. Transportation Safety Bureau (NTSB) said hours after the detection of the wreckage, a team of investigators sent to the scene identified the aircraft: it is the Bellanca 8kcab, which disappeared on September 3, 2007, when Fosset took off from Yerington in Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, still in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fosset’s personal items were found by a couple near their Mammoth Lakes home.
These are two documents named Fosset, both issued by the Illinois Federal Aviation Administration, cash cash and a pull.
Fossett's search was stopped a month after his disappearance.
The billionaire had won a place in history thanks to a long series of records.
In 2002, he became the first man to complete the world round on an aerostatic balloon: two weeks of solo flight.
Three years later, he had travelled around the world by plane and without a stop.
Among all these records, also that of flying at 15,445 meters high, over the Andes, but with a co-pilot.
